service.name: Amazon CloudWatch Logs
service.documentation: Amazon CloudWatch Logs enables you to monitor, store, and access your system, application, and custom log files.

cabal.name: Amazon CloudWatch Logs
cabal.description: Amazon CloudWatch Logs enables you to monitor, store, and access your system, application, and custom log files.

operations.name: CreateLogGroup
operations.documentation:
Creates a new log group with the specified name. The name of the log group must be unique within a region for an AWS account. You can create up to 500 log groups per account.

You must use the following guidelines when naming a log group:

  • Log group names can be between 1 and 512 characters long.
  • Allowed characters are a-z, A-Z, 0-9, '_' (underscore), '-' (hyphen), '/' (forward slash), and '.' (period).

operations.name: CreateLogStream
operations.documentation:
Creates a new log stream in the specified log group. The name of the log stream must be unique within the log group. There is no limit on the number of log streams that can exist in a log group.

You must use the following guidelines when naming a log stream:

  • Log stream names can be between 1 and 512 characters long.
  • The ':' colon character is not allowed.

operations.name: DeleteLogGroup
operations.documentation: Deletes the log group with the specified name and permanently deletes all the archived log events associated with it.

operations.name: DeleteLogStream
operations.documentation: Deletes a log stream and permanently deletes all the archived log events associated with it.

operations.name: DeleteMetricFilter
operations.documentation: Deletes a metric filter associated with the specified log group.

operations.name: DeleteRetentionPolicy
operations.documentation: Deletes the retention policy of the specified log group. Log events would not expire if they belong to log groups without a retention policy.

operations.name: DescribeLogGroups
operations.documentation:
Returns all the log groups that are associated with the AWS account making the request. The list returned in the response is ASCII-sorted by log group name.

By default, this operation returns up to 50 log groups. If there are more log groups to list, the response would contain a nextToken value in the response body. You can also limit the number of log groups returned in the response by specifying the limit parameter in the request.

contents.name: _dlgNextToken
contents.documentation: A string token used for pagination that points to the next page of results. It must be a value obtained from the response of the previous DescribeLogGroups request.

contents.name: _dlgLimit
contents.documentation: The maximum number of items returned in the response. If you don't specify a value, the request would return up to 50 items.

optional.name: _dlgNextToken
optional.documentation: A string token used for pagination that points to the next page of results. It must be a value obtained from the response of the previous DescribeLogGroups request.

optional.name: _dlgLimit

fields.name: _dlgLimit

fields.name: _dlgNextToken
fields.documentation: A string token used for pagination that points to the next page of results. It must be a value obtained from the response of the previous DescribeLogGroups request.

operations.name: GetLogEvents
operations.documentation:
Retrieves log events from the specified log stream. You can provide an optional time range to filter the results on the event timestamp.

By default, this operation returns as much log events as can fit in a response size of 1MB, up to 10,000 log events. The response will always include a nextForwardToken and a nextBackwardToken in the response body. You can use any of these tokens in subsequent GetLogEvents requests to paginate through events in either forward or backward direction. You can also limit the number of log events returned in the response by specifying the limit parameter in the request.

contents.name: _gleNextToken
contents.documentation: A string token used for pagination that points to the next page of results. It must be a value obtained from the nextForwardToken or nextBackwardToken fields in the response of the previous GetLogEvents request.

contents.name: _gleLimit
contents.documentation: The maximum number of log events returned in the response. If you don't specify a value, the request would return as much log events as can fit in a response size of 1MB, up to 10,000 log events.

contents.name: _gleStartFromHead
contents.documentation: If set to true, the earliest log events would be returned first. The default is false (the latest log events are returned first).

optional.name: _gleNextToken
optional.documentation: A string token used for pagination that points to the next page of results. It must be a value obtained from the nextForwardToken or nextBackwardToken fields in the response of the previous GetLogEvents request.

optional.name: _gleLimit
optional.documentation: The maximum number of log events returned in the response. If you don't specify a value, the request would return as much log events as can fit in a response size of 1MB, up to 10,000 log events.

operations.name: PutLogEvents
operations.documentation:
Uploads a batch of log events to the specified log stream.

Every PutLogEvents request must include the sequenceToken obtained from the response of the previous request. An upload in a newly created log stream does not require a sequenceToken.

The batch of events must satisfy the following constraints:

  • The maximum batch size is 32,768 bytes, and this size is calculated as the sum of all event messages in UTF-8, plus 26 bytes for each log event.
  • None of the log events in the batch can be more than 2 hours in the future.
  • None of the log events in the batch can be older than 14 days or the retention period of the log group.
  • The log events in the batch must be in chronological ordered by their timestamp.
  • The maximum number of log events in a batch is 1,000.

contents.name: _pleSequenceToken
contents.documentation: A string token that must be obtained from the response of the previous PutLogEvents request.

optional.name: _pleSequenceToken
optional.documentation: A string token that must be obtained from the response of the previous PutLogEvents request.

fields.name: _pleSequenceToken
fields.documentation: A string token that must be obtained from the response of the previous PutLogEvents request.

operations.name: PutMetricFilter
operations.documentation: Creates or updates a metric filter and associates it with the specified log group. Metric filters allow you to configure rules to extract metric data from log events ingested through PutLogEvents requests.

operations.name: PutRetentionPolicy
operations.documentation: Sets the retention of the specified log group. A retention policy allows you to configure the number of days you want to retain log events in the specified log group.

operations.name: TestMetricFilter
operations.documentation: Tests the filter pattern of a metric filter against a sample of log event messages. You can use this operation to validate the correctness of a metric filter pattern.
